05570nam a22006615i 9780226820279DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021040663  a9780226820279  a(DE-B1597)624337  a(OCoLC)1296428168  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJK2271b.K35 2022 4aJK2271b.K35 2022 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a320.9732231 aKalmoe, Nathan P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRadical American Partisanship :bMapping Violent Hostility, Its Causes, and the Consequences for Democracy /cLilliana Mason, Nathan P. Kalmoe. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b45 line drawings, 7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in American Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Recognizing Partisan Extremes -- tChapter 2. Radical Historical Roots -- tChapter 3. Radical Partisan Psychology -- tPart I. Identifying Radical Partisans -- tChapter 4. The Scope of Radicalism -- tChapter 5. Trends: Stumbling toward a Breakdown -- tChapter 6. Who Are the Radical Partisans? -- tPart II. Radical Behaviors and the Impact of Conditions and Events -- tChapter 7. From Radical Views to Aggressive Behavior -- tChapter 8. Historical Precedents and Reasons for Violence -- tChapter 9. Reactions to Election Losses and Violent Events -- tPart III. Communicating Radicalism -- tChapter 10. Words Matter -- tChapter 11. The Future of Radical Partisanship: Risks and Opportunities -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRadical partisanship among ordinary Americans is rising, and it poses grave risks for the prospects of American democracy. Political violence is rising in the United States, with Republicans and Democrats divided along racial and ethnic lines that spurred massive bloodshed and democratic collapse earlier in the nation’s history. The January 6, 2021 insurrection and the partisan responses that ensued are a vivid illustration of how deep these currents run. How did American politics become so divided that we cannot agree on how to categorize an attack on our own Capitol? For over four years, through a series of surveys and experiments, Nathan P. Kalmoe and Lilliana Mason have been studying radicalism among ordinary American partisans. In this groundbreaking book, they draw on new evidence—as well as insights from history, psychology, and political science—to put our present partisan fractiousness in context and to explain broad patterns of political and social change. Early chapters reveal the scope of the problem, who radical partisans are, and trends over time, while later chapters identify the conditions that partisans say justify violence and test how elections, political violence, and messages from leaders enflame or pacify radical views. Kalmoe and Mason find that ordinary partisanship is far more dangerous than pundits and scholars have recognized. However, these findings are not a forecast of inevitable doom; the current climate also brings opportunities to confront democratic threats head-on and to create a more inclusive politics. Timely and thought-provoking, Radical American Partisanship is vital reading for understanding our current political landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aParty affiliationzUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPolitical violencezUnited States. 0aRadicalismzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apartisanship, violence, public opinion, U.S. politics.1 aMason, Lilliana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook pack